This is an intriguing story. It's not written poorly at all if that's what you're worried about, the initial premise is well explained and both the characters react fairly believably to each other and their situation. Providing a danger bigger than the both of them is a very good idea that spices up the scenario well, as well as having her be a competent person with her own agenda in the first place. There were even some nice little touches, like her not being able to sit properly on the couch because of her tail.

I do have a few gripes however. I feel like he takes her appearance too well in stride at the start. If I found a strange lizard creature that couldn't or wouldn't talk in my trash, the last thing on my mind would be welcoming it into my home - even if it was wearing clothes, you could stand to have explored why he did that a bit more.
Secondly I think you could stand to make your paragraphs a bit shorter, to more neatly separate topics and important info. I almost missed the description of the alien because it was bundled up in the middle of a big paragraph where you talk first about the room he's in, and last about how he's considering it possibly being a hallucination. It was all competently written and well phrased, but if you organized it a bit more carefully it would be much easier to read.
The scene with the monsters was tense, but I do think the way he hit the wolf stretched believability considering how you described its build. I'm not sure if that's due to some property the things have that you haven't explained yet, but if you'd had even a short sentence of him reacting to it in like a 'I can't believe that worked' way I think it would have sold that hit much better.

All in all though you nail the most important aspects of a story, which is making a compelling and interesting situation and characters. You write very well all in all, and I will definitely be waiting for moreComment too long Verification not required.
